[src:vitest-testing/assertion-software-development] The Boolean expression must be a compile-time constant value, for example `(sizeof(int)==4)` would be a valid expression in that context.
[src:vitest-testing/assertion-software-development] This construct does not work at file scope (i.e., not inside a function), and so it must be wrapped inside a function.
[src:vitest-testing/assertion-software-development] If the `(BOOLEAN CONDITION)` part evaluates to false, then the above code will not compile because arrays may not have a negative length.
[src:vitest-testing/assertion-software-development] If, in fact, the compiler allows a negative length, then the initialization byte (the `'!'` part) should cause even such over-lenient compilers to complain.
[src:vitest-testing/assertion-software-development] The Boolean expression must be a compile-time constant value, for example `(sizeof(int) == 4)` would be a valid expression in that context.
[src:vitest-testing/assertion-software-development] Both of these methods require a method of constructing unique names.
[src:vitest-testing/assertion-software-development] Modern compilers support a `__COUNTER__` preprocessor define that facilitates the construction of unique names, by returning monotonically increasing numbers for each compilation unit.
[src:vitest-testing/assertion-software-development] D provides static assertions through the use of `static assert`.
[src:vitest-testing/assertion-software-development] Most languages allow assertions to be enabled or disabled globally, and sometimes independently.
[src:vitest-testing/assertion-software-development] Assertions are often enabled during development and disabled during final testing and on release to the customer.
[src:vitest-testing/assertion-software-development] Not checking assertions avoids the cost of evaluating the assertions while (assuming the assertions are free of side effects) still producing the same result under normal conditions.
[src:vitest-testing/assertion-software-development] Under abnormal conditions, disabling assertion checking can mean that a program that would have aborted will continue to run.
[src:vitest-testing/assertion-software-development] Some languages, including C, YASS, and C++, can completely remove assertions at compile time using the preprocessor.
[src:vitest-testing/assertion-software-development] Similarly, launching the Python interpreter with "-O" (for "optimize") as an argument will cause the Python code generator to not emit any bytecode for asserts.
[src:vitest-testing/assertion-software-development] Java requires an option to be passed to the run-time engine in order to *enable* assertions.
[src:vitest-testing/assertion-software-development] Absent the option, assertions are bypassed, but they always remain in the code unless optimised away by a JIT compiler at run-time or excluded at compile time via the programmer manually placing each assertion behind an `if (false)` clause.
[src:vitest-testing/assertion-software-development] Programmers can build checks into their code that are always active by bypassing or manipulating the language's normal assertion-checking mechanisms.
[src:vitest-testing/assertion-software-development] Assertions are distinct from routine error-handling.
[src:vitest-testing/assertion-software-development] Assertions document logically impossible situations and discover programming errors: if the impossible occurs, then something fundamental is clearly wrong with the program.
[src:vitest-testing/assertion-software-development] This is distinct from error handling: most error conditions are possible, although some may be extremely unlikely to occur in practice.
[src:vitest-testing/assertion-software-development] Using assertions as a general-purpose error handling mechanism is unwise: assertions do not allow for recovery from errors; an assertion failure will normally halt the program's execution abruptly; and assertions are often disabled in production code.
[src:vitest-testing/assertion-software-development] Assertions also do not display a user-friendly error message.
[src:vitest-testing/assertion-software-development] Here, the programmer is aware that `malloc` will return a `NULL` pointer if memory is not allocated.
[src:vitest-testing/assertion-software-development] This is possible: the operating system does not guarantee that every call to `malloc` will succeed.
[src:vitest-testing/assertion-software-development] If an out-of-memory error occurs, the program will immediately abort.
[src:vitest-testing/assertion-software-development] Without the assertion, the program would continue running until `ptr` was dereferenced, and possibly longer, depending on the specific hardware being used.
[src:vitest-testing/assertion-software-development] So long as assertions are not disabled, an immediate exit is assured.
[src:vitest-testing/assertion-software-development] But if a graceful failure is desired, the program has to handle the failure.
[src:vitest-testing/assertion-software-development] For example, a server may have multiple clients, or may hold resources that will not be released cleanly, or it may have uncommitted changes to write to a datastore.
[src:vitest-testing/assertion-software-development] In such cases, it is better to fail a single transaction than to abort abruptly.
[src:vitest-testing/assertion-software-development] Another error is to rely on the side effects of expressions used as arguments of an assertion.
[src:vitest-testing/assertion-software-development] One should always keep in mind that assertions might not be executed at all, since their sole purpose is to verify that a condition which should always be true does, in fact, hold true.
[src:vitest-testing/assertion-software-development] Consequently, if the program is considered to be error-free and released, assertions may be disabled and will no longer be evaluated.
